NESTED SHADOW DOM HANDLING - SELENIUM 4

1. Locate First Shadow Host
2. Use getShadowRoot()
3. Store it in SearchContext
4. Locate Second Shadow Host inside First Shadow Root
5. Use getShadowRoot() again
6. Store it in another SearchContext
7. Continue until the target element is reached
8. Use CSS Selectors only

Syntax:

// First Shadow Host
WebElement host1 = driver.findElement(By.cssSelector("#host1"));
SearchContext root1 = host1.getShadowRoot();

// Second Shadow Host
WebElement host2 = root1.findElement(By.cssSelector("#host2"));
SearchContext root2 = host2.getShadowRoot();

// Third Shadow Host (if available)
WebElement host3 = root2.findElement(By.cssSelector("#host3"));
SearchContext root3 = host3.getShadowRoot();

// Target Element
WebElement ele = root3.findElement(By.cssSelector("span"));

-----------------------------------------------------

Example:

WebElement host1 = driver.findElement(By.cssSelector("#shadow-root"));
SearchContext root1 = host1.getShadowRoot();

WebElement host2 = root1.findElement(By.cssSelector("#inner-shadow-dom"));
SearchContext root2 = host2.getShadowRoot();

WebElement element = root2.findElement(By.cssSelector("span"));

System.out.println(element.getText());

-----------------------------------------------------

Interview Points:

✔ Selenium 4 introduced getShadowRoot()
✔ getShadowRoot() returns SearchContext
✔ SearchContext is used to locate elements inside Shadow DOM
✔ Nested Shadow DOMs require multiple getShadowRoot() calls
✔ CSS Selectors are supported
✔ XPath is NOT supported inside ShadowRoot
✔ Works only for Open Shadow DOMs
✔ Closed Shadow DOMs cannot be accessed directly through Selenium

Flow:

Shadow Host 1
    ↓
getShadowRoot()
    ↓
Shadow Root 1
    ↓
Shadow Host 2
    ↓
getShadowRoot()
    ↓
Shadow Root 2
    ↓
Target Element